50|$|In addition, the Office {{is charged}} with {{conducting}} cost analyses relating to the Supplemental Security Income (SSI) program, a general-revenue financed, means-tested program for low-income aged, blind and disabled people. The Office provides technical and consultative services to the Commissioner, to the Board of Trustees of the <b>Social</b> <b>Security</b> <b>Trust</b> <b>Funds,</b> and its staff appears before Congressional Committees to provide expert testimony on the actuarial aspects of <b>Social</b> <b>Security</b> issues.|$|R
50|$|The {{government}} {{adopted a}} unified {{budget in the}} Johnson administration in 1968. This change resulted in a single measure of the fiscal status of the government, based on {{the sum of all}} government activity. The surplus in <b>Social</b> <b>Security</b> <b>trust</b> <b>funds</b> offsets the total debt, making it appear much smaller than it otherwise would. This allowed Congress to increase spending without having to risk the political consequences of raising taxes.|$|R
